orkshire, England","Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England","Sai, Normandy, France":"Sai, Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1060–":"1060–Deceased","1046–Male":"1046–Deceased","1059–1090":"1059–1090","1060–Male":"1060–Deceased","1063–1139":"1063–1139","1074–Male":"1074–Deceased","–1146":"–1146","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1085–1129":"1085–1129","1022–1092":"1022–1092","1026–1077":"1026–1077","1090":"1090","1066":"1066","1077":"1077","1022":"1022","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1074":"1074","1063":"1063","1060":"1060","1092":"1092","Abt 1054":"about 1054","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1026":"1026","1059":"1059","1146":"1146","1046":"1046","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England":"Kirby Knowle, Yorkshire, England","Sai, Normandy, France":"Sai, Orne, Normandy, France","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lascelles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laswell","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Lascelles  . This surname is also found as   Lacefield  ."]},{"name":"Lasell","meanings":["English: variant of   Lascelles  ."]},{"name":"Lacelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":46,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey de Lascelles was born in 1060, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Picot de Lascelles, I, High Sheriff of Cambridgeshire, was 39 and his mother, Hugolina de Gernon, was 34. He married Matilda. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in England."},"et":{"1060–":"1060–Surnud","1046–Ma